{"source_key":"sha256-d1b343ed42a51085ffb3fbb074863c4f","record_index":2737,"record_hash":"sha256:daa15427a3fe9b47e8afe1ebf8eff07f6c218e67cd05e132d2ff4f4c2c4ef97c","timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:16:47.084Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yeah. The useful pattern is **not onboarding-as-a-tour**. For a chat skill, the winning pattern is closer to **capability discovery + recipes + contextual recovery**.\n\nI’d steal from four places:\n\n1. **Agent Skills / Claude Skills: progressive disclosure**\n   Agent Skills work by showing only name + description up front, then loading full instructions/resources only when relevant. The description is the key trigger surface. Sources call this progressive disclosure: discovery → activation → resources/scripts.  \n   Sources: [Agent Skills spec](https://agentskills.io/client-implementation/adding-skills-support), [Claude Skills docs](https://docs.claude.com/en/docs/claude-code/skills), [Microsoft Agent Skills](https://learn.microsoft.com/mt-mt/agent-framework/agents/skills).\n\n2. **Slack apps: explicit help + entry-point-aware onboarding**\n   Slack recommends `[REDACTED:path] help` when slash commands matter, and says onboarding should differ depending on how the user entered the app. That maps well to agents: “commit my changes” should not trigger the same guidance as “ship it.”  \n   Sources: [Slack slash command docs](https://docs.slack.[REDACTED:entropy]), [Slack onboarding](https://api.slack.com/start/designing/onboarding).\n\n3. **Alexa skills: welcome/help prompts with exact next utterances**\n   Alexa skill docs push a simple rule: tell the user what the skill does, and end with a concrete thing they can say next. Also: built-in help should be contextual.  \n   Source: [Alexa prompt design](https://developer.amazon.com/en-US/docs/alexa/interaction-model-design/design-the-prompts-for-your-skill.html).\n\n4. **Product onboarding: quick win, contextual, not front-loaded**\n   Intercom and general onboarding guidance consistently point toward contextual help and first-use success, not dumping docs up front. Empty states and product tours work when they push the user toward the next useful action, not when they explain the whole product.  \n   Sources: [Intercom product tours best practices](https://www.intercom.[REDACTED:entropy]), [UserOnboard empty states](https://www.useronboard.[REDACTED:entropy]).\n\n**What this means for GitButler**\nI would not make the skill chatty. I’d add a small **“What can I ask GitButler agents to do?”** capability, plus tighten the agent recipes.\n\nSomething like:\n\n```md\nIf the user asks what GitButler/but can help with, answer with 4-6 task-shaped examples, not a command list:\n\n- \"commit my changes\" — create a focused branch/commit and verify nothing relevant is left behind\n- \"ship it\" — commit, push, and open/update a PR\n- \"move this change to another branch\" — use `but move`, `stage`, `amend`, or `uncommit` depending on shape\n- \"fix my branch stack\" — inspect status and move branches/commits safely\n- \"recover after a failed but command\" — refresh IDs with `but status -fv` and retry with fresh IDs\n```\n\nThen in the operating rules:\n\n```md\nAfter a successful commit, do not automatically push unless the user asked to ship/publish/share/open a PR.\n\nIf the user did ask to ship:\n1. verify status\n2. push\n3. create or update PR\n4. report the branch/commit/PR\n\nIf a file/change/commit ID fails:\n1. do not retry the stale ID\n2. run `but status -fv`\n3. use fresh IDs\n4. explain only if recovery changes the workflow\n```\n\nSo the “onboarding” is mostly invisible: the agent learns task recipes and recovery patterns. The user-facing part is just a compact help response when they ask what they can do. That’s the right level of friction.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:16:47.084Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}